solutions.content:
My first approach was to think of a queue before and one after our scanned day that in turn would reveal to us if the day was auspicious for a robbery or not.

And thus I proceeded, first of all cutting a few edge cases out:
* if the time `t` is `0`, then each single element is valid and we can just overwrite `sec` with `iota` to be a succession of `sec.size()` elements starting from `0`, right before `return`ing it;
* conversely, if `t` was less than half `sec.size()`, no point in proceeding either, since we know already that no valid day can match our condition in terms of valid range, so we can just `return` an empty vector.

With that out of the table, we can focus on our core, general logic, declaring a few support variables:
* `len` will store the how many days we need to parse;
* `before` and `after` are aptly named queues which will store all the matching days as we progress;
* `res` is our accumulator variable where we will store our final result.

Time to parse `sec`, using two pointers, `l` set to `0` and `m` set to `t` (that we increase now for convenience later); going on until `m < len`, and increasing them at each iteration, we will:
* reset `before` if it has at least one element and its last element is less then the one currently pointed by `l`;
* push said element (`sec[l]`) into `before`;
* specularly, reset `after` if it has at least one element and its last element is less then the one currently pointed by `m`;
* push said element (`sec[m]`) into `after`;
* check if the length of both `before` or `after` matches the current value of `t` (the original one, increased by `1`) and in case store the current index `m` into `res`, since we now know it's a valid one;
* pop the front of `before` if its length is nw `t`;
* pop the front of `after` if its length is nw `t`.

Once done, we can just `return` `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> goodDaysToRobBank(vector<int>& sec, int t) {
        // edge cases
        if (!t) {
            iota(begin(sec), end(sec), 0);
            return sec;
        }
        if (2 * t > sec.size()) return {};
        // support variables
        int len = sec.size();
        queue<int> before, after;
        vector<int> res;
        // preparing before and after
        for (int l = 0, m = t++; m < len; l++, m++) {
            if (before.size() && before.back() < sec[l]) {
                before = queue<int> ();
            }
            before.push(sec[l]);
            if (after.size() && after.back() > sec[m]) {
                after = queue<int> ();
            }
            after.push(sec[m]);
            if (before.size() == t && after.size() == t) res.push_back(l);
            if (before.size() == t) before.pop();
            if (after.size() == t) after.pop();
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Do we actually care if we have more than the minimum amount of valid days in front of us? Not at all, so we might risk sacrificing a bit more memory (but it does not seem to be the case, running a few test cases) and avoid popping altogether from either queue, in this slightly quicker version:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> goodDaysToRobBank(vector<int>& sec, int t) {
        // edge cases
        if (!t) {
            iota(begin(sec), end(sec), 0);
            return sec;
        }
        if (2 * t > sec.size()) return {};
        // support variables
        int len = sec.size();
        queue<int> before, after;
        vector<int> res;
        // building before and after
        for (int l = 0, m = t++; m < len; l++, m++) {
            if (before.size() && before.back() < sec[l]) {
                before = queue<int> ();
            }
            before.push(sec[l]);
            if (after.size() && after.back() > sec[m]) {
                after = queue<int> ();
            }
            after.push(sec[m]);
            if (before.size() >= t && after.size() >= t) res.push_back(l);
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

But, hey! Now that we put it this way, we do not even need to proceed with queues, since we would be just inserting elements in following the same order they have in `sec`; it might be much leaner and memory efficient if instead we rely on 4 pointers now, a pair each to delimit our `before` and `after` range, modifying the code like this and getting a crazy improvement (half the time, less than half the space!):

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> goodDaysToRobBank(vector<int>& sec, int t) {
        // edge cases
        if (!t) {
            iota(begin(sec), end(sec), 0);
            return sec;
        }
        if (2 * t > sec.size()) return {};
        // support variables
        int len = sec.size();
        vector<int> res;
        // updating before and after range pointers
        for (int i = 0, l = 0, j = t, m = t; m < len; l++, m++) {
            if (l && sec[l - 1] < sec[l]) {
                i = l;
            }
            if (sec[m - 1] > sec[m]) {
                j = m;
            }
            if (l - i >= t && m - j >= t) res.push_back(l);
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

Notice that this runs in just one pass, whereas we need at least two passes for a typical DP here; I tried to run it just for the sake of it and it was definitely a bit slower, since computing everything in advance and storing it was really not necessary.

To my surprise, the performance is basically the same as the solution above:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> goodDaysToRobBank(vector<int>& sec, int t) {
        // edge cases
        if (!t) {
