solutions.content:
for each day we need to know how many day to it's left and to it's right have security >=. This can be done if we do two sweeps on array and check if every next (and prior) day is less secure => it security value is less than a previous value.  Otherwise the chain is broken we can reset our counting. So we actually only care about immidiate neighbour and not all previous days.

We this information finding a good day is a matter of checking if for this day number of more secure days to the left and to the right are both >= than a time. This again can be done in one scan.

We can optimize initial two scans and two arrays into one scan and one 2d array.

O(n) time - scan security array once to collect number of more secure days left-to-right and right-to-left, another scan to find good days
O(n) space - need [N][2] array to store number of more secure neighbouring days

```
    public List<Integer> goodDaysToRobBank(int[] security, int time) {
        List<Integer> res = new ArrayList();
        int N = security.length;
        int[][] counts = new int[N][2];
        for (int i = 1; i < N; i++) {
            //fill right to left part
            if (security[i - 1] >= security[i]) {
                counts[i][0] = counts[i - 1][0] + 1; 
            } 
            //fill left to right part
            int ltorIdx = N - i - 1;
            if (security[ltorIdx] <= security[ltorIdx + 1]) {
                counts[ltorIdx][1] = counts[ltorIdx + 1][1] + 1; 
            } 
        }
        //i represents the potential day for robbery
        for (int i = time; i < N - time; i++) {
            if (counts[i][0] >= time && counts[i][1] >= time) {
                res.add(i);
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
```

