solutions.content:
This kind of problem is usually solved by sliding window or prefix sum/count. Sliding window usually wins on space usage.
In this case, we use 2 sliding windows: non-increasing `[deci..decj]` and non-decreasing `[inci..incj]`.
Both have fixed size `time`, and it always has `decj = incj - time`. We just need to shrink the left.
Codes are straight forward:
```
    public IList<int> GoodDaysToRobBank(int[] security, int time) {
        var res = new List<int>();
        // sliding window [deci..decj] and [inci..incj], decj == incj - time
        int deci = 0, decj = -time, inci = 0, incj = 0;
        for (; incj < security.Length; decj++, incj++) {
            if (decj > 0 && security[decj-1] < security[decj]) // against dec
                deci = decj;
            if (deci + time < decj)  // window too large
                deci++;

            if (incj > 0 && security[incj-1] > security[incj]) // against inc
                inci = incj;
            if (inci + time < incj)  // window too large
                inci++;

            if (deci + time == decj && decj == inci)
                res.Add(decj);
        }

        return res;
    }
```

