# Approach

We create a vector of per-day analyse and for each day we store whether in the original array there's enough left and right days. We default-initialize days with "Ok", and then only update a day when it turns out not to be "ok".

Since we need to consider days both on the left and right sides, we do that simultaneously in the same cycle.

The obvious optimization here is that each cycle instead of cycling through `time` elements on the left and right side we simply store/update the index of the last found "bad" day, then we calculate the distance to it from the current day.

After we did that for every day, it is only a matter of gathering all "okayish" days from the vector and returning the result. The easiest way would be to do that in a separate cycle *(this wouldn't influence $$O()$$ anyway)*, but for just for the sake of exercise I put it in the same cycle where calculation is done.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$

# Code
```c++
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> goodDaysToRobBank(const vector<int>& security, int time) {
        enum State {Ok, Bad};
        vector<State> days_analysis(security.size());
        int i_left_bad_days = -1, i_mirrored_right_bad_days = -1;
        vector<int> ret;
        const size_t i_indices_meet_location = (security.size() + 2) / 2 -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < security.size(); ++i) {
            if (i > 0 && security[i-1] < security[i]) {
                i_left_bad_days = i-1;
            }
            if (i - i_left_bad_days -1 < time)
                days_analysis[i] = Bad;

            size_t i_right = security.size() - 1 - i;
            if (i > 0 && security[i_right] > security[i_right+1]) {
                i_mirrored_right_bad_days = i-1;
            }
            if (i - i_mirrored_right_bad_days -1 < time)
                days_analysis[i_right] = Bad;

            if (i >= i_indices_meet_location) {
                if (days_analysis[i] == Ok)
                    ret.push_back(i);
                if (days_analysis[i_right] == Ok && i != i_right)
                    ret.push_back(i_right);
            }
        }
        return ret;
    }
};
```

