# Intuition
This problem can be solved with prefix and suffix arrays: just scan left to right and right to left annotating the positions where the previous *time* values in security were monotonically increasing / decreasing.
Then match the positions where both prefix and suffix arrays satisfy the requirements.
This solution has linear complexity O(3n).
There's no need, though to do it in three passages: it can be done in a single one.


# Approach
The algorithm goes as this:
* if the security array is not large enough to account for pre and post observations, then it's a trivial empty answer
* otherwise, allocate an array *dp* where we'll store how many favourable conditions have we measured: this will be 0 for no conditions, 1 for either pre or post and 2 for both of them.
* keep the head of the result list in *result*. We'll prepend each day to it to keep complexity O(1)
* scan left to right on i and keep count of the consecutive non-increasing days: if an increase is detected, reset the counter. Do the same from the right end.
* if days from left are greater or equal than the *time* threshold, increase the count in *dp*. If the count has reached 2, it means this day is a good one: add it to the result
* do the same for the right side
* return the *result* list

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)

- Space complexity:
O(n)

# Code
```
object Solution {
    def goodDaysToRobBank(security: Array[Int], time: Int): List[Int] = {
        if (security.length < time * 2 + 1) {
            List.empty
        } else {
            val dp = Array.ofDim[Int](security.length) 
            var pre = 0
            var post = 0
            var result = List.empty[Int]
            (0 until security.length).foreach { i =>
                if (i > 0 && security(i) <= security(i - 1)) {
                    pre += 1
                } else {
                    pre = 0
                }
                if (i > 0 && security(security.length - i - 1) <= security(security.length - i)) {
                    post += 1
                } else {
                    post = 0
                }
                if (pre >= time) {
                    dp(i) += 1
                    if (dp(i) == 2) {
                        result = i :: result
                    }
                }
                if (post >= time) {
                    dp(security.length - 1 - i) += 1
                    if (dp(security.length - 1 - i) == 2) {
                        result = (security.length - 1 - i) :: result
                    }
                }
            }
            result
        }
    }
}
```

