# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
If one bomb explodes and the bombs that comes inside its range, it's the indication that its a dfs/bfs problem

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Here, i have discussed the dfs approach, just running dfs for each bomb (with a new visited array each time) to see how many bombs will explode if that bomb explodes, and then take max out of all.
I have set the ans initially to one, cause in the worst case 1 bomb will always explode as given in question

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n^2), In the worst case for all dfs calls all bombs will be visited
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
- n = no. of bombs
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int dfs(vector<vector<int>>& bombs, int i, vector<int>& visited){
        int n = bombs.size();
        visited[i]=1;
        // return 1 + dfs call to the bombs in ranges if not visited

        int output = 1;
        for(int j=0;j<n;j++){
            double tot_dist = sqrt(pow(bombs[i][0]-bombs[j][0],2) + pow(bombs[i][1]-bombs[j][1],2));
            if(visited[j]==0 && tot_dist<=bombs[i][2]){
                output+= dfs(bombs,j,visited);
            }
        }
        return output;
    }

    int maximumDetonation(vector<vector<int>>& bombs) {
        // I guess my approach after thinking would be a dfs approach, if a bomb denotes dfs to the bomb in its ranges and return the max output out of all dfs calls
        int n = bombs.size();

        int ans = 1;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            vector<int> visited(n,0);
            ans = max(ans,dfs(bombs,i,visited));
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

