# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The crucial part is to create the directed graph, i.e. the adjacent list. The bombs are the the vertice. If bomb[j] is within the bomb range of bomb[i], there is a directed edge from bomb[i] to bomb[j]. Then either of DFS or BFS can be applied for solving this problem.

According the radius of bomb range, sort the bombs in descending order. Then create adjacent list according to Euclidean distance fomula:
$$
d^2((x, y),(x_j, y_j))=(x-x_j)^2+(y-y_j)^2\leq r^2  \qquad(1)
$$
where $(x, y,r)$ is the info for the  detonating bomb[i] and the bomb[j] with coordinates $(x_j, y_j)$ lies within the bomb[i] range. The computation for the inequality needs to use long long int to prevent overflow! But there are many cases that the bomb is closed to the detonating bomb.

So, we used firstly the easy computing to test whether
$$
|x-x_j|+|y-y_j|\leq r \qquad(2)
$$
if the inequality  (2) that's fine add j to adj[i], if not then try the inequality (1) for Euclidean distance fomula. It is clear if the inequality (2) is satisfied, then the inequalty (1) is valid since the triangle inequality.
