solutions.content:
Thought Process in Brief: 

I thought about the relation between any two bombs. It appeared every (bomb1,bom2) pair can be represented with true/false. i.e does triggering bomb2 triggers bomb1? So I created a matrix with **(i,j)==true**, if: **j**th bomb triggers **i**th bomb

I thought about triggering every one of them one by one. I was initially thinking in the lines of a 1D dp, which was wrong since the problem can't be broked down in smaller subproblem with some function f,z such that: f(n)=z(f(n-1)) *[Think about it]*

Observing the relation i.e. the matrix, it appeared as an adjacency matrix, So the problem must be modelable as a graph with ***bombs as nodes*** and the ***relations as directed edges***. 

Voila, it is a question of finding the node from which maximum nodes can be traversed in the connected component. (which can be done using dfs) 


```
class Solution {
public:
    bool inrange(int x1,int y1,int r1,int x2,int y2,int r2){
        long long int x=abs(x1-x2);
        long long int y=abs(y1-y2);
        long long int r=abs(r2);
        return x*x+y*y<=r*r;
    }
    int maximumDetonation(vector<vector<int>>& bombs) {
        int n=bombs.size();
        vector<vector<bool>> v(n,vector<bool>(n,false));
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++)
                if(inrange(bombs[i][0],bombs[i][1],bombs[i][2],bombs[j][0],bombs[j][1],bombs[j][2]))
                    v[i][j]=true;
        }
        int maxi=0;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            vector<int> visited(n,-1);
            int num=1;
            if(visited[i]==-1) dfs(v,visited,num,i);
            maxi=max(maxi,num);
        }
        return maxi;
    }
    void dfs(vector<vector<bool>>& v,vector<int>& visited,int& num,int cur){
        visited[cur]=num;
        for(int i=0;i<visited.size();i++){
            if(visited[i]==-1 and v[i][cur])
                dfs(v,visited,++num,i);
        }
    }
};
```

