# Intuition
A new bomb explodes if its distance to the current bomb is less than the radius of the current bomb. 
We can calculate this with a^2 + b^2 = c^2
We can use BFS to check which bombs explodes, by adding exploding boms to our queue. 
We have to check what the maximum number of exploding bombs is for each starting bomb, since order matters here, which is fine, since there are only 100 bombs

# Approach
BFS

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n^2)

- Space complexity:
not sure, we only create one queue and one set at a time, so O(n)?
# Code
```
/**
 * @param {number[][]} bombs
 * @return {number}
 */
var maximumDetonation = function(bombs) {
    let answer = 0
    for (let i  = 0; i < bombs.length; i++) {
        const exploded = new Set([i])
        const queue = [bombs[i]]
        while(queue.length > 0) {
            const bomb = queue.shift()
            for (let j = 0; j < bombs.length; j++) {
                if (exploded.has(j)) continue
                const newBomb = bombs[j]
                const distance = ((Math.abs(newBomb[0] - bomb[0])**2 )+ (Math.abs(newBomb[1] - bomb[1])**2)) ** 0.5
                if (distance <= bomb[2]) {
                    queue.push(newBomb)
                    exploded.add(j)
                }
            }
        }
        answer = Math.max(exploded.size, answer)
    }
    return answer
};
```

